        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>
** Prediction of Disk Surface Brightness based on SED Models:

We use the disk geometric parameters in Backman et al. (2009) in our
SED modeling to simulate model images for observational
planning. Although SED models are known to be degenerate, they are the
best means to estimate the disk surface brightness when proper grain
properties are incorporated. We adopt the simplest assumptions in the
SED modeling: a uniform grain size distribution with a power index of
-3.5 at all radii, and grain properties of compact silicates from
sub-um to 1000 um, which are adequate for material near and inside the
ice line. The model surface brightness is computed assuming a face-on,
axis-symmetric geometry (no density enhancement/clump), then inclined
to 25 degree from face-on. Therefore, our approach represents a
pessimistic view of the system to ensure a strong detection in
reality.


Given the derived dust temperature (~150 K) from the Spitzer IRS
excess (Backman et al. 2009), sub-um to blackbody-like grains confined
in a zone of 1.5 to 3.5 AU from the star would yield such a
temperature. We compute the disk surface brightness at several ALMA
continuum bands. After considering the tradeoff between angular
resolution and sensitivity, we decide Band 7 at a beam of 0.5'' is
best suited to reach our goal. Similar calculation is performed for
the outer warm belt.


** Request Sensitivity:

Our request integration depth is motivated by a need to achieve a
reasonable S/N for the innermost warm belt. The stellar photosphere is
1.2 mJy at 870 um, while the peak flux of the warm belt is 0.04
mJy/beam at the 0.5'' resolution. With a rms noise of 9 uJy/beam in a
total of 8.7 hours on-source integration time, the innermost warm belt
can be detected at 4 sigma. Note that if the width of the belt turns
out to be much narrower than the assumed value (2 AU), the actual
signal-to-noise will be significantly higher (our asteroid belt is
only 1 AU wide). With the full ALMA 50 12-m array, the integration
time would be reduced to 5 hours for the same S/N, which is still an
expensive project (~10 hours including overheads). We request a total
of 18.2 hours in cycle 2 to complete this project.
 

** Correlator:

This project is driven by continuum sensitivity, therefore, we set the
correlator for the maximum bandwidth (7.5 GHz). We also include a
low-resolution line observation configuration to serendipitously
search for CO(3-2) at 0.84 km/s resolution (the expected line width is
~ twice of the Keplerian velocity at 3/20 AU, i.e., 24/9 km/s).
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
