    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>
ALMA observations of debris disks can reveal both the structures
associated with planet formation (e.g., asteroid belts at the ice
line) and, indirectly, the presence of planets that are far below our
current capabilities for direct detection. Eps Eri is the Rosetta
Stone for these studies. It is by far the closest prominent debris
disk (allowing superb physical resolution); it is around a star
similar to the Sun (0.8 M_sun); and it is of similar age to the next
two closest prominent disks (Vega and Fomalhaut), facilitating direct
comparisons without correcting for disk evolution. The ALMA primary
beam at 870 um covers the entire region around this star corresponding
to the Solar System within the Kuiper Belt (after correcting for the
lower stellar luminosity). We propose a deep image at this wavelength
to study two debris rings identified from spectral modeling, one
possibly corresponding to the ice line and the other with strong
signatures of planetary sculpting. This program will provide a lasting
legacy for understanding the relation of more distant and hence
unresolved debris disks (known around more than 400 stars) to
exoplanetary systems.
</prp:abstract>
